{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":21086,"record_hash":"sha256:4602e45a43a453d9afb018763f95e1d9dfe5cdeb17536342f8652fe54d049af3","timestamp":"2026-05-10T20:34:37.288Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Yes, this is the right thing to think about now. I think the **data shape is still pointed in the right direction**, but the **read ergonomics in GitMeta are only half-built**.\n\nFor the two future use cases in [future-use-cases.md](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/agent-session-capture/future-use-cases.md:1):\n\n**Session Handoff**\nA reader would roughly do:\n\n```rust\nlet project = session.target(&Target::parse(\"project\")?);\n\nlet session_keys = project.get_value(\"gitbutler:agent-sessions\")?;\nfor session_key in session_keys {\n    read gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:updated-at\n    read gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:sources\n    read gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:transcript\n}\n```\n\nThen it would turn transcript records into an agent-friendly context stream using `role`, `content_text`, `tool_name`, `event_kind`, and fallback `source_record`.\n\n**Code Review Context**\nA future branch/PR/change target would first point back to sessions:\n\n```text\n<branch/change/pr target>\n  gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n```\n\nThen the reader resolves those keys on the `project` target and renders the same transcript timeline. That part of the model still feels right: relationships point to sessions; they do not copy transcript data.\n\nWhere GitMeta feels a bit underpowered is reading typed shapes back out.\n\nRight now we have:\n\n- `get_value(key)` returning `Option<MetaValue>`\n- `get_all_values(prefix)`\n- `list_entries(key)`\n- `set_record(prefix, struct)` for writing record-shaped metadata\n\nThe missing symmetry is noticeable:\n\n1. **`set_record` has no read-side pair**\n\nWe can write:\n\n```rust\nhandle.set_record(prefix, source)?;\n```\n\nBut reading it back requires manually calling `get_all_values`, stripping prefixes, matching value types, and reconstructing the struct.\n\nA natural API would be something like:\n\n```rust\nlet source: TranscriptSource = handle.get_record(prefix)?;\n```\n\nImplementation idea: gather `prefix:*` string fields, build a JSON object, deserialize with serde. Missing fields stay absent, so `Option<T>` works naturally.\n\n2. **Sets are too manual**\n\nSession indexes and future relationships are sets, so readers will constantly do:\n\n```rust\nmatch handle.get_value(\"gitbutler:agent-sessions\")? {\n    Some(MetaValue::Set(values)) => ...\n    None => empty,\n    Some(_) => error,\n}\n```\n\nA small GitMeta helper would make this cleaner:\n\n```rust\nlet sessions = handle.set_members(\"gitbutler:agent-sessions\")?;\n```\n\nProbably missing key returns an empty set.\n\n3. **JSON list values are too manual**\n\nTranscripts are stored as JSON strings inside a GitMeta list. Readers will need:\n\n```rust\nlet entries = handle.list_entries(transcript_key)?;\nlet records = entries\n    .into_iter()\n    .map(|entry| serde_json::from_str::<TranscriptRecord>(&entry.value))\n```\n\nA generic helper would be useful later:\n\n```rust\nlet records: Vec<ListEntry<TranscriptRecord>> =\n    handle.list_json_entries(transcript_key)?;\n```\n\nI would **not** add pagination yet, but that may become real once transcripts get large.\n\nMy take: we probably do **not** need to change the stored agentlog shape right now. The shape in [gitmeta-data-model.md]([REDACTED:entropy].md:1) supports both future use cases well enough.\n\nBut before building real readers, I would consider adding three small GitMeta read APIs:\n\n```rust\nget_record<T>(&self, prefix: &str) -> Result<T>\nset_members(&self, key: &str) -> Result<BTreeSet<String>>\nlist_json_entries<T>(&self, key: &str) -> Result<Vec<ListEntry<T>>>\n```\n\nThen `but-agentlog` can later expose its own domain reader, so app/CLI/web code never spells raw keys like `gitbutler:agent-session:<key>:transcript`. That would keep GitMeta generic and keep the agentlog schema owned by `but-agentlog`.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-10T20:34:37.288Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}